  <sect1 xml:id="cha.introduction">
    <info>
      <title>Introduction to hoe-manns</title>
    </info>
    <sect2 xml:id="sec.introduction">
      <info>
        <title>Introduction</title>
      </info>
      <indexterm>
        <primary>Introduction</primary>
      </indexterm>
      <para><productname>hoe-manns</productname> is an extension of the
          <application>Ruby</application> rake/rubygems helper for project Rakefiles
          <application>hoe</application> (see <link xlink:href="https://github.com/seattlerb/hoe"
          >https://github.com/seattlerb/hoe</link>.) It extends the standard
          <application>Ruby</application> tasks to some new useful tasks.</para>

      <para>To use the software you will need an installed <application>Ruby</application> version
        (Higher or equal 2.2.0), <application>bundler-audit</application> and an installed and
        already configured <application>hoe</application>.</para>
    </sect2>
    <sect2 xml:id="sec.installation">
      <info>
        <title>Installation</title>
      </info>
      <indexterm>
        <primary>Installation</primary>
      </indexterm>
      <para>For installing you have to type in your user shell: &prompt.user;<command>gem install
          hoe-manns</command>.</para>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>

  <sect1 xml:id="sec.usage">
    <info>
      <title>How to use <productname>Ruby</productname> in your projects</title>
    </info>
    <indexterm>
      <primary>Usage</primary>
    </indexterm>
    <para>First, you have to open the <filename>Rakefile</filename> of your project and writes there
      near the <filename>Hoe.spec</filename> line:</para>
    <para>
      <code>Hoe.plugin :manns</code>
    </para>
    <para><code>Hoe.spec 'your project' do ...</code>
    </para>
    <para><code>end</code>
    </para>
    <para>Sure now you have to add <productname>hoe-manns</productname> as a dependency in your
        <filename>Rakefile</filename> and generate a new <filename>Gemfile</filename> now. Then
        <productname>hoe-manns</productname> is ready to work.</para>
  </sect1>

  <sect1 xml:id="sec.tasks">
    <info>
      <title>The Tasks</title>
    </info>
    <indexterm>
      <primary>Rake Tasks</primary>
    </indexterm>
    <para><productname>hoe-manns</productname> integrates some additional
        <application>Rake</application>-Tasks as explained in the next table.</para>
    <para>
      <table frame="all">
        <title>The Rake Tasks</title>
        <tgroup cols="2">
          <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
          <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2" colwidth="1.0*"/>
          <thead>
            <row>
              <entry>Task</entry>
              <entry>Effect</entry>
            </row>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <row>
              <entry> &prompt.user;<command>rake bundler:gemfile_lock</command>
              </entry>
              <entry>updates a <filename>Gemfile.lock</filename> (does a '<command>bundle
                  update</command>')</entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry> &prompt.user;<command>rake bundler:gemfile_install</command>
              </entry>
              <entry>generates a new Gemfile.lock (does a '<command>bundle
                install</command>')</entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry> &prompt.user;<command>rake bundle-audit:run</command>
              </entry>
              <entry>downloads the actual security warnings from
                  <application>bundle-audit</application> and checks possible problems by the
                dependencies.</entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry> &prompt.user;<command>rake clean-pkg</command>
              </entry>
              <entry>checks if a "<filename>pkg</filename>" directory is present, if then it will be
                deleted.</entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry> &prompt.user;<command>rake copy_master</command>
              </entry>
              <entry>it expects a branch "develop" and merges the new stuff into the master branch.
                Then it runs a rake <command>git:tag</command> and returns again into the develop
                branch.</entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry> &prompt.user;<command>rake remove_pre_gemspec</command>
              </entry>
              <entry>checks the presence of a Pre-Gemspec (a generated file for test cases) and
                deletes them.</entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry> &prompt.user;<command>rake run_before_release</command>
              </entry>
              <entry>runs the task in that order: git:manifest, bundler:gemfile,
                bundler:gemfile_lock, gem:spec_remove, bundle_audit:run, copy_master.</entry>
            </row>
          </tbody>
        </tgroup>
      </table>
    </para>
  </sect1>

